Description

This challenge demonstrates why sensitive validation should never be implemented on the client side (JavaScript). The flag is hidden within the frontend logic and can be extracted by analyzing the code.


Objective

Analyze the client-side JavaScript and reconstruct the hidden flag.

Step 1 — Accessing the Website

The challenge page contains a password input field.

Entering random inputs results in "Incorrect password"

No visible hints are shown

This suggests that validation happens on the client side


Step 2 — Inspecting the Source Code

Steps:

Right-click → Inspect

Go to Sources / Debugger

Locate the JavaScript function responsible for validation


Step 3 — Extracting the JavaScript Logic

function verify() {
  checkpass = document.getElementById("pass").value;
  split = 4;

  if (checkpass.substring(0, split) == 'pico') {
    if (checkpass.substring(split*6, split*7) == 'eb02') {
      if (checkpass.substring(split, split*2) == 'CTF{') {
        if (checkpass.substring(split*4, split*5) == 'ts_p') {
          if (checkpass.substring(split*3, split*4) == 'lien') {
            if (checkpass.substring(split*5, split*6) == 'lz_2') {
              if (checkpass.substring(split*2, split*3) == 'no_c') {
                if (checkpass.substring(split*7, split*8) == 'b45}') {
                  alert("Password Verified")
                }
              }
            }
          }
        }
      }
    }
  } else {
    alert("Incorrect password");
  }
}


Step 4 — Understanding the Logic

The password is split into 8 parts, each containing 4 characters:

Index Range	Value
0–4	pico
4–8	CTF{
8–12	no_c
12–16	lien
16–20	ts_p
20–24	lz_2
24–28	eb02
28–32	b45}


Step 5 — Reconstructing the Flag

pico + CTF{ + no_c + lien + ts_p + lz_2 + eb02 + b45}


✅ Final Flag

picoCTF{no_clients_plz_2eb02b45}


What I Learned

Client-side code is fully visible and reversible

JavaScript should never contain sensitive data

Attackers can reconstruct logic easily

Always validate on the server side


Vulnerability Concept

Client-Side Validation Vulnerability

Sensitive logic exposed in frontend

No backend verification

Easily bypassable security


